 Male''\n| Darwen\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=3| 2007\n| ''[[Hotel Babylon]]''\n| Robert Kane\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| ''[[Agatha Christie's Marple|Marple: At Bertram's Hotel]]''\n| Mr. Humfries\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Stardust (2007 film)|Stardust]]''\n| Prince Tertius\n|\n|-\n|2008\u20132011\n|''[[Lark Rise to Candleford (TV series)|Lark Rise to Candleford]]''\n|Thomas Brown\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" | 2008\n|''[[Skins (UK TV series)|Skins]]''\n| Graham Miles\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| ''[[Love Soup]]''\n| Douglas McVitie\n|\n|-\n| ''[[No Heroics]]''\n| Lightkiller\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| ''The Pro''\n| \n| Short\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 2009\n| ''[[Desperate Romantics]]''\n| [[Charles Dickens]]\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Cast Offs]]''\n| Darren\n| 1 episode\n|-\n|rowspan=4| 2010\n| ''Lizzie and Sarah''\n| Michael\n|\n|-\n| ''[[The Great Outdoors (UK TV series)|The Great Outdoors]]''\n| Bob\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Fable III]]''\n| Brian\n| Video game\n|-\n| ''[[Single Father (TV series)|Single Father]]''\n| Robin\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=1| 2010, 2015\n| ''[[Miranda (TV series)|Miranda]]''\n| Anthony\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n|rowspan=3| 2011\n| ''[[Holy Flying Circus]]''\n| Andrew Thorogood\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Misfits (TV series)|Misfits]]''\n| Jonas\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| ''Miso Soup''\n| Shash\n| Short\n|-\n| 2011\u2013present\n| ''[[Friday Night Dinner]]''\n| Jim Bell\n|31 episodes\n|-\n|rowspan=6| 2012\n|-\n| ''[[The Indian Doctor]]''\n| Rev Herbert Todd\n|\n|-\n| ''[[A Moody Christmas]]''\n| Heathrow Passenger\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| ''[[Outnumbered (UK TV series)|Outnumbered]]''\n| Norris\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Spy (2011 TV series)|Spy]]''\n| Philip\n|\n|-\n| ''Is This a Joke?''\n|\n| Short\n|-\n|2012\u20132016\n| ''[[The Increasingly Poor Decisions of Todd Margaret]]''\n| Lord Mountford\n| 4 episodes\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" | 2013\n| ''[[Heading Out]]''\n| Brian\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| ''All Stars''\n| Simon Tarrington\n|\n|-\n| ''[[The World's End (film)|The World's End]]''\n| Publican 7\n|\n|-\n|''[[Midsomer Murders]]''\n|Simon Fergus-Johnson\n|1 episode (series 16 episode 1)\n|-\n|2014\n| ''[[Death in Paradise (TV series)|Death in Paradise]]''\n| \n| 1 episode (series 3 episode 6)\n|-\n|2015\n| ''We're Doomed! The Dad's Army Story''\n| [[Clive Dunn]]\n| \n|-\n|2016\u2013present\n|''[[Upstart Crow]]''\n|[[Robert Greene (dramatist)|Robert Greene]]\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=3|2016\n|''[[The Comedian's Guide to Survival]]''\n|Pick Up Driver\n|\n|-\n|''[[Endeavour (TV series)|Endeavour]]''\n|[|Felix Lorimer\n| 1 episode (series 3, episode 4)\n|-\n| ''[[Maigret (2016 TV series)|Maigret]]''\n| Doctor Moers\n|\n|-\n|2017\n| ''[[Murder on the Blackpool Express]]''\n| Graham\n|\n|-\n|2017, 2018\n|''[[Benidorm (TV series)|Benidorm]]'' \n| Malcolm/Dennis\n| 3 episodes (series 9, episodes 7 and 8 and series 10, episode 7)\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2020\n|''[[Intelligence_(British_TV_series)|Intelligence]]''\n| Barnaby Bailer\n|\n|-\n|''The Trouble with Maggie Cole''\n| Peter Cole\n|}\n\n==Advertising work==\nIn 2009 he appeared as a car salesman in a [[SEAT]] television advert. Heap voices the fox in the [[Old Speckled Hen]] adverts sponsoring comedy on [[Dave (TV channel)|Dave]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thepublican.com/story.asp?storyCode=66988 |title=Old Speckled Hen renews sponsorship of Tchannel Dave|first=James|last=Wilmore|work=[[The Publican]] magazine|accessdate=15 April 2011|date=7 May 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Other acting==\nIn 2008 Heap played the role of Widmerpool in a Radio 4 serialisation of [[Anthony Powell]]'s ''[[A Dance to the Music of Time]]''. He played Eliza's husband in 2006 [[BBC Radio 4|Radio 4]] play ''The Eliza Stories'' and appeared as Marmite the Dwarf in the short-lived Radio 4 sitcom ''[[The Sofa of Time]]''. He starred in the music video for [[Four Tet]]'s single \"[[Everything Ecstatic|Smile Around the Face]]\" in 2005, contributed a multitude of character voices in the audiobook \"Do Ants Have Arseholes?\". In 2012 he starred as Martin in the [[BBC Radio 4|Radio 4]] play ''Cordite for Breakfast'', a comedy about Napoleonic-era battle re-enactments.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01kjt7r|title=''Cordite for Breakfast''|publisher=BBC|accessdate=5 December 2012|date=10 July 2010}}</ref> In March 2013, he appeared as Rincewind in a 4-part Radio 4 adaptation of Terry Pratchett's ''Eric''. He also played the angel Aziraphale in the 2014 BBC radio adaption of [[Neil Gaiman]] and [[Terry Pratchett]]'s ''[[Good Omens]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Brown|first1=Brigid|title=BBC Radio Brings Neil Gaiman and Terry Pratchett's Good Omens to Life|url=http://www.bbcamerica.com/anglophenia/2014/09/bbc-radio-brings-neil-gaiman-terry-pratchetts-good-omens-life/|accessdate=6 September 2014|publisher=BBC America|date=5 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|372423}}\n*[http://www.curtisbrown.co.uk/mark-heap/ Agency profile]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Heap, Mark}}\n[[Category:Indian emigrants to England]]\n[[Category:English puppeteers]]\n[[Category:English male film actors]]\n[[Category:English male comedians]]\n[[Category:English male radio actors]]\n[[Category:English male television actors]]\n[[Category:English male voice actors]]\n[[Category:English people of American descent]]\n[[Category:Jugglers]]\n[[Category:People from Tamil Nadu]]\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Indian people of American descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=November 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name = Mark Heap\n|image = \n|caption = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=y|1957|5|13}}<ref>[https://www.hellomagazine.com/profiles/mark-heap/ Mark Heap\u2013Biography]. ''[[Hello! (magazine)|Hello!]]'' website. Retrieved 28 March 2020</ref>\n|birth_place = [[Kodaikanal]], [[Tamil Nadu]], [[India]]<ref name=\"imdb\">{{cite web\n|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0372423/\n|title=Mark Heap\n|accessdate=5 October 2008\n|website=IMDb}}</ref>\n|occupation = [[Actor]] \n|years_active = 1983\u2013present\n|known_for = ''[[Friday Night Dinner]]'' <br/>''[[Green Wing]]'' <br/>''[[Spaced]]'' <br/>''[[Upstart Crow]]''\n}}\n'''Mark Heap''' (born in India, 13 May 1957) is an English actor, best known for his roles in television comedies including: ''[[Benidorm_(TV_series)|Benidorm]]'', ''[[Brass Eye]]'', ''[[Big Train]]'', ''[[Jam (TV series)|Jam]]'', ''[[Green Wing]]'', ''[[Upstart Crow]]'' and ''[[Friday Night Dinner]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nHeap was born in [[Tamil Nadu]], India, to an English father and American mother, the youngest of four boys.{{cn|date=March 2020}} He began his acting career in the 1980s as a member of the Medieval Players, a touring company performing medieval and early modern theatre, and featuring [[Stilts|stilt-walking]], [[juggling]] and [[puppetry]]. His brother, Carl Heap, was the artistic director of the company.<ref>{{cite news|first=Carl |last=Heap |url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2014/jun/12/medieval-theatre-shakespeare-carl-heap |title=Finding the method in medieval theatre's madness |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=25 January 2016}}</ref> After its demise, he became part of the [[street theatre]] duo ''The Two Marks'' (with Mark Saban)<ref>{{cite news|first=Catherine |last=Love |url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2014/jun/12/medieval-theatre-shakespeare-carl-heap |title=Mark Heap: Mr Zany buttons up |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=3 April 2014 |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref> who appeared on television shows ''[[Ghost Train (TV series)|Ghost Train]]'' and ''[[3-2-1]]''.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\n==Television==\nHeap has appeared in a variety of television comedy roles, often playing obsessive and self-deluded characters and drama including struggling artist Brian Topp in ''[[Spaced]]'', the pompous [[Alan Statham|Dr. Alan Statham]] in ''[[Green Wing]]'', and various roles in the [[sketch comedy|sketch]] show ''[[Big Train]]'', many scenes of which he improvised.<ref>{{Cite web | title = Big Train at 20 - interview with Arthur Matthews | work = The Digital Fix | date = 23 July 2018 | accessdate = 13 August 2018 | url = https://www.thedigitalfix.com/television/content/11789/big-train-at-20-an-interview-with-the-shows-co-creator-arthur-matthews/}}</ref> He has worked in a number of ventures with [[Chris Morris (satirist)|Chris Morris]], appearing in ''[[Jam (TV series)|Jam]]'', its radio predecessor ''[[Blue Jam]]'', and the documentary parody series ''[[Brass Eye]]''. He voiced the lead character of Eric Feeble in the animated comedy ''[[Stressed Eric]]''. Other recurring roles included Terry Roche in [[Paul Whitehouse]]'s comedy-drama ''[[Happiness (TV series)|Happiness]]'' and Derek Few in ''[[How Do You Want Me?]]''. He played Harry in the short-lived [[Rob Grant]] TV series ''[[The Strangerers]]'', aired in 2000. He also guested in the second series of the BBC comedy ''[[Look Around You]]'' as Leonard Hatred.\n\nHe appeared in the 2007 [[BBC One]] drama ''[[Hotel Babylon]]'' as an unsuccessful businessman who became a [[bellboy]]. Between 2008 and 2010 he appeared in 32 episodes of the BBC period drama ''[[Lark Rise to Candleford (TV series)|''Lark Rise to Candleford'']]'' as head postman Thomas Brown, as well as super villain Lightkiller in an episode of the sitcom ''[[No Heroics]]''. He also appears as the father of [[Chris Miles (Skins)|Chris Miles]] in the [[Channel 4]] programme ''[[Skins (UK TV series)|Skins]]''. Heap played the love interest of the main character in the second series of the BBC comedy ''[[Love Soup]]''. He played the role of [[Charles Dickens]] in the 2009 [[BBC Two]] drama ''[[Desperate Romantics]]''. Also that he played [[Jessica Hynes]]' husband in the one-off comedy ''Lizzie & Sarah'', written by Hynes and [[Julia Davis]].\n\nIn 2010 Heap appeared as Bob Stevens, the leader of a [[rambling]] group in the BBC4 series ''[[The Great Outdoors (UK TV series)|The Great Outdoors]]''. He also appeared as a [[psychiatrist]] in [[Miranda Hart]]'s comedy ''[[Miranda (TV series)|Miranda]]'' on BBC2. In October 2010 he appeared as Robin in the four-part BBC drama ''[[Single Father (TV series)|Single Father]]''. Heap plays Jim Bell in the Channel 4 sitcom ''[[Friday Night Dinner]]'' alongside [[Simon Bird]] and [[Tamsin Greig]]. He also played Andrew Thorogood in the [[BBC Four]] comedy ''[[Holy Flying Circus]]'' and Jonas in the 8th episode of [[E4 (channel)|E4]]'s sci-fi comedy-drama ''[[Misfits (TV series)|Misfits]]'' series 3.\n\nHe joined the cast of the [[Sky1]] original series ''[[Spy (2011 TV series)|Spy]]'' for its second season commencing in October 2012, replacing [[Tom Goodman-Hill]] as Philip Quil, Judith's partner and Marcus' headteacher. He appeared in the spin-off episode of ''[[Outnumbered (UK TV series)|Outnumbered]]'', the Christmas special episode, aired on 24 December 2012 in which he portrayed Norris, for this single episode. He played the owner of a pet crematorium in [[Sue Perkins]]'s 2013 comedy ''[[Heading Out]]''. Mark also had a leading role in BBC Radio 4's adaptation of Gogol's 'Lost Souls.' He starred as [[Robert Greene (dramatist)|Robert Greene]] in three seasons of ''[[Upstart Crow]]'' (2016\u20132018), a BBC 2 sitcom about Shakespeare, written by [[Ben Elton]]. His co-stars included [[David Mitchell (comedian)|David Mitchell]], Harry Enfield, Rob Rouse, Gemma Whelan and Liza Tarbuck. He also appeared as Dr John Hall in the stage show based on the programme.\n\nHeap also starred in recent series of the sitcom [[Benidorm]], in which he played the character Malcolm Barrett, the controlling and manipulative boyfriend of Pauline Maltby.\nHeap's 2020 roles continues with playing headmaster and husband in ITV's 'The Trouble with Maggie Cole' alongside Dawn French\n\n==Film==\nIn 1983, Heap made a brief appearance as a fire-breather in the [[James Bond]] film [[Octopussy]]. He played a school teacher in the 2002 film [[About a Boy (film)|''About a Boy'']]. He appeared in [[Tim Burton]]'s 2005 ''[[Charlie and the Chocolate Factory (film)|Charlie and the Chocolate Factory]]''. He played supporting roles in ''[[Confetti (2006 film)|Confetti]]'' (2006), ''Tunnel of Love'' (2004), ''[[Stardust (2007 film)|Stardust]]'' (2007), and ''[[The World's End (film)|The World's End]]'' (2013). In 2008 he co-starred in the surreal science fiction film ''[[Captain Eager and the Mark of Voth]]''.\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|1997\n| ''[[Bring Me the Head of Mavis Davis]]''\n| Duncan\n| \n|-\n|2002\n| ''[[About a Boy (film)|About A Boy]]''\n| Maths teacher\n|\n|-\n|2004\n|''[[The Calcium Kid]]''\n| Sebastian Gore-Brown\n|\n|-\n||2005\n| ''[[Charlie and the Chocolate Factory (film)|Charlie and the Chocolate Factory]]''\n| Man with Dog\n|\n|-\n|2008\n| ''[[Captain Eager and the Mark of Voth]]''\n| Scrutty Baker\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|''The Midnight Gang''\n| Sir Quentin\n| TV Movie\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1987\n| ''The Les Dennis Laughter Show''\n| The Two Marks\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 1990\n| ''[[Up Yer News]]''\n| Film Assistant\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 1992\n| ''[[Packet of Three (TV series)|Packing Them In]]''\n| Fire eating stiltwalker\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 1993\n| ''[[Viva Cabaret]]''\n| The Two Marks\n| 1 episode\n|-\n|rowspan=3| 1994\n| ''[[The Bill]]''\n| Chris Boxer\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| ''Seaforth''\n| Capt. Karl Von Berner\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| ''How High The Moon''\n|\n|\n|-\n| 1995\n| ''[[The World of Lee Evans]]''\n| Platform Guard\n| 1 episode\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 1997\n| ''Hospital''\n| Dr. Ralph Crosby\n|\n|-\n| ''An Unsuitable Job for a Woman''\n| DS Maskell\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 1997\u20131998\n| ''[[Alas Smith and Jones|Smith and Jones]]''\n| \n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 1997\u20132001\n| ''[[Brass Eye]]''\n| Various roles\n|\n|-\n| 1998\n| ''[[Kiss Me Kate (TV series)|K