ford]]''\n|Thomas Brown\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" | 2008\n|''[[Skins (UK TV series)|Skins]]''\n| Graham Miles\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| ''[[Love Soup]]''\n| Douglas McVitie\n|\n|-\n| ''[[No Heroics]]''\n| Lightkiller\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| ''The Pro''\n| \n| Short\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 2009\n| ''[[Desperate Romantics]]''\n| [[Charles Dickens]]\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Cast Offs]]''\n| Darren\n| 1 episode\n|-\n|rowspan=4| 2010\n| ''Lizzie and Sarah''\n| Michael\n|\n|-\n| ''[[The Great Outdoors (UK TV series)|The Great Outdoors]]''\n| Bob\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Fable III]]''\n| Brian\n| Video game\n|-\n| ''[[Single Father (TV series)|Single Father]]''\n| Robin\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=1| 2010, 2015\n| ''[[Miranda (TV series)|Miranda]]''\n| Anthony\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n|rowspan=3| 2011\n| ''[[Holy Flying Circus]]''\n| Andrew Thorogood\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Misfits (TV series)|Misfits]]''\n| Jonas\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| ''Miso Soup''\n| Shash\n| Short\n|-\n| 2011\u2013present\n| ''[[Friday Night Dinner]]''\n| Jim Bell\n|31 episodes\n|-\n|rowspan=6| 2012\n|-\n| ''[[The Indian Doctor]]''\n| Rev Herbert Todd\n|\n|-\n| ''[[A Moody Christmas]]''\n| Heathrow Passenger\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| ''[[Outnumbered (UK TV series)|Outnumbered]]''\n| Norris\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Spy (2011 TV series)|Spy]]''\n| Philip\n|\n|-\n| ''Is This a Joke?''\n|\n| Short\n|-\n|2012\u20132016\n| ''[[The Increasingly Poor Decisions of Todd Margaret]]''\n| Lord Mountford\n| 4 episodes\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" | 2013\n| ''[[Heading Out]]''\n| Brian\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| ''All Stars''\n| Simon Tarrington\n|\n|-\n| ''[[The World's End (film)|The World's End]]''\n| Publican 7\n|\n|-\n|''[[Midsomer Murders]]''\n|Simon Fergus-Johnson\n|1 episode (series 16 episode 1)\n|-\n|2014\n| ''[[Death in Paradise (TV series)|Death in Paradise]]''\n| \n| 1 episode (series 3 episode 6)\n|-\n|2015\n| ''We're Doomed! The Dad's Army Story''\n| [[Clive Dunn]]\n| \n|-\n|2016\u2013present\n|''[[Upstart Crow]]''\n|[[Robert Greene (dramatist)|Robert Greene]]\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=3|2016\n|''[[The Comedian's Guide to Survival]]''\n|Pick Up Driver\n|\n|-\n|''[[Endeavour (TV series)|Endeavour]]''\n|[|Felix Lorimer\n| 1 episode (series 3, episode 4)\n|-\n| ''[[Maigret (2016 TV series)|Maigret]]''\n| Doctor Moers\n|\n|-\n|2017\n| ''[[Murder on the Blackpool Express]]''\n| Graham\n|\n|-\n|2017, 2018\n|''[[Benidorm (TV series)|Benidorm]]'' \n| Malcolm/Dennis\n| 3 episodes (series 9, episodes 7 and 8 and series 10, episode 7)\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2020\n|''[[Intelligence_(British_TV_series)|Intelligence]]''\n| Barnaby Bailer\n|\n|-\n|''The Trouble with Maggie Cole''\n| Peter Cole\n|}\n\n==Advertising work==\nIn 2009 he appeared as a car salesman in a [[SEAT]] television advert. Heap voices the fox in the [[Old Speckled Hen]] adverts sponsoring comedy on [[Dave (TV channel)|Dave]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thepublican.com/story.asp?storyCode=66988 |title=Old Speckled Hen renews sponsorship of Tchannel Dave|first=James|last=Wilmore|work=[[The Publican]] magazine|accessdate=15 April 2011|date=7 May 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Other acting==\nIn 2008 Heap played the role of Widmerpool in a Radio 4 serialisation of [[Anthony Powell]]'s ''[[A Dance to the Music of Time]]''. He played Eliza's husband in 2006 [[BBC Radio 4|Radio 4]] play ''The Eliza Stories'' and appeared as Marmite the Dwarf in the short-lived Radio 4 sitcom ''[[The Sofa of Time]]''. He starred in the music video for [[Four Tet]]'s single \"[[Everything Ecstatic|Smile Around the Face]]\" in 2005, contributed a multitude of character voices in the audiobook \"Do Ants Have Arseholes?\". In 2012 he starred as Martin in the [[BBC Radio 4|Radio 4]] play ''Cordite for Breakfast'', a comedy about Napoleonic-era battle re-enactments.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01kjt7r|title=''Cordite for Breakfast''|publisher=BBC|accessdate=5 December 2012|date=10 July 2010}}</ref> In March 2013, he appeared as Rincewind in a 4-part Radio 4 adaptation of Terry Pratchett's ''Eric''. He also played the angel Aziraphale in the 2014 BBC radio adaption of [[Neil Gaiman]] and [[Terry Pratchett]]'s ''[[Good Omens]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Brown|first1=Brigid|title=BBC Radio Brings Neil Gaiman and Terry Pratchett's Good Omens to Life|url=http://www.bbcamerica.com/anglophenia/2014/09/bbc-radio-brings-neil-gaiman-terry-pratchetts-good-omens-life/|accessdate=6 September 2014|publisher=BBC America|date=5 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|372423}}\n*[http://www.curtisbrown.co.uk/mark-heap/ Agency profile]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Heap, Mark}}\n[[Category:Indian emigrants to England]]\n[[Category:English puppeteers]]\n[[Category:English male film actors]]\n[[Category:English male comedians]]\n[[Category:English male radio actors]]\n[[Category:English male television actors]]\n[[Category:English male voice actors]]\n[[Category:English people of American descent]]\n[[Category:Jugglers]]\n[[Category:People from Tamil Nadu]]\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Indian people of American descent]]\n", "name_user": "Bob6925151418", "label": "vandal", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eTelevision)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mark_Heap"}
{"title_page": "Chicago (album)", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Chicago\n| type       = Studio album\n| artist     = [[Chicago (band)|Chicago]]\n| cover      = ChicagoAlbum.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = January 26, 1970<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.columbiarecords.com/timeline/#!date=1915-06-05_18:57:53!|website=360 Sound: The Columbia Records Story|title=125 Years of Columbia Records|publisher=Sony Music Entertainment|access-date=November 14, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171114143057/http://www.columbiarecords.com/timeline/#!date=1915-06-05_18:57:53!|archive-date=November 14, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| recorded   = August 1969\n| venue      =\n| studio     = [[CBS 30th Street Studio|Columbia Recording Studios]], [[New York City|New York]] and [[CBS Columbia Square|Columbia Studios]], [[Hollywood]]\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Jazz rock]]|[[progressive rock]]|[[hard rock]]}}\n| length     = 67:21\n| label      = [[Columbia Records|Columbia]]\n| producer   = [[James William Guercio]]\n| prev_title = [[Chicago Transit Authority (album)|Chicago Transit Authority]]\n| prev_year  = 1969\n| next_title = [[Chicago III]]\n| next_year  = 1971\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Chicago\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Make Me Smile]]/[[Colour My World (Chicago song)|Colour My World]]\n | single1date = March 1970\n | single2     = [[25 or 6 to 4]]\n | single2date = June 1970\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Chicago''''' is the second studio album by [[Chicago]]-based American [[rock and roll|rock]] band [[Chicago (band)|Chicago]].  Like their debut album, ''[[Chicago Transit Authority (album)|Chicago Transit Authority]]'', this was a double album.  It was their first album under the name Chicago (the band's prior name, Chicago Transit Authority, was changed due to a threatened lawsuit from the [[Chicago Transit Authority]]) and the first to use the now ubiquitous [[cursive writing|cursive]] Chicago logo on the cover. Released in January 1970 on [[Columbia Records]], ''Chicago'' was commercially successful. It was certified gold by the [[Recording Industry Association of America certification|Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA) in April of the same year of its release, and certified platinum in 1991. It reached No. 4 on the album charts in the United States and No. 6 on the album charts in the [[United Kingdom|UK]], and produced three top ten singles on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. The album received three [[Grammy Award]] nominations - for [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]], [[Grammy Award for Best Pop Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocals|Contemporary Vocal Group]], and [[Grammy Award for Best Recording Package|Best Album Cover]]. It was voted best album of 1970 by readers of ''[[Cashbox (magazine)|Cash Box]]'' magazine, and the 1971 best small-combo [[LP record|LP]] by readers of ''[[Playboy]]'' magazine.\n\n==History==\nThe album was released in 1970 after the band had shortened its name from \"The Chicago Transit Authority\" following the release of their self-titled [[Chicago Transit Authority (album)|debut album]] the previous year, in order to avoid legal action being threatened by the [[Chicago Transit Authority|actual mass-transit company]]. The official title of the album is ''Chicago'', although it came to be known as '''''Chicago II''''', keeping it in line with the succession of Roman numeral-titled albums that officially began with ''[[Chicago III]]'' in 1971.\n\n''Chicago Transit Authority'' was a success, yet ''Chicago'' is considered by many to be the group's breakthrough album, yielding three singles that made it into the top ten of the Billboard Hot 100, including \"[[Make Me Smile]]\" (number 9), \"[[Colour My World (Chicago song)|Colour My World]]\" (number 7), and \"[[25 or 6 to 4]]\" (number 4).<ref name=\"Chicago Hot 100\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/music/chicago/chart-history/hot-100|title=Chicago Chart History: Hot 100|work=Billboard|access-date=November 8, 2017}}</ref> \n\n''Chicago'' was released in January 1970 on Columbia Records and was an instant hit, reaching number 4 on the Billboard 200 in the United States<ref name=\"Billboard 200\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/music/chicago/chart-history/billboard-200|title=Chicago Chart History: Billboard 200|work=Billboard|access-date=November 8, 2017}}</ref> and number 6 in the UK.<ref name=\"UK album chart\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/search/albums/chicago/|title=Chicago {{!}} full Official Chart History {{!}} Official Charts Company|access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> Columbia Records was very active in promoting its quadraphonic four-channel surround-sound format in the mid-1970s, and nine of Chicago's first ten albums were made available in quad.  The quad mix features elements not heard in the standard stereo mix, including additional guitar work from Kath in \"25 Or 6 To 4\" and a different vocal take from Lamm in \"Wake Up Sunshine,\" which reveals a different lyric in the song's last line.\n\nIn 2002, ''Chicago'' was remastered and reissued on one CD by Rhino Records with the single versions of \"Make Me Smile\" and \"25 or 6 to 4\" as bonus tracks. Rhino released a DVD-Audio version of the album in 2003, featuring both Advanced Resolution Stereo and 5.1 surround sound mixes. In 2016, British producer and musician [[Steven Wilson]] remixed Chicago from the original multitrack tapes. This version was released on January 27, 2017 by Rhino Records.<ref>{{AllMusic |class=album/release|id=mr0004652426|tab= |label=Chicago II Steven Wilson Remix|last= |first= |accessdate={{date|2017-02-17|mdy}}}}</ref> A vinyl edition of the remix cut by Kevin Gray was released on August 11, 2017. [[Robert Lamm]] stated in an interview that the album has been nominated for the Grammy Hall of Fame more than once.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sunherald.com/news/local/news-columns-blogs/by-the-way/article181885271.html|title=Chicago\u2019s Robert Lamm on revisiting \u2018Chicago II\u2019 and the band\u2019s long and winding road|last=Clark|first=Jeff|date=October 31, 2017|work=Sun Herald|access-date=May 16, 2018|location=Gulfport, Mississippi, USA|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Musical style, writing, composition==\nIn a 2015 article, ''Classic Rock Review'' says the album saw Chicago's, \"full immersion into mainstream success while still building on their fusion of rock, funk and jazz.\"<ref name=classicrockrev>{{Cite web|url=http://www.classicrockreview.com/tag/midwest-artists/page/2/|title=Chicago II|date=July 3, 2015|website=Classic Rock Review|language=en-US|access-date=January 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn Danny Seraphine's book ''Street Player'', he describes it this way: \"In between the dates of our touring schedule, we somehow found the opportunity to jump into CBS Studios in Los Angeles and record a second album in August 1969. Whereas the first record was a compilation of raw energy, we took a more controlled approach to our new effort.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=\"Street Player: My Chicago Story|last=Seraphine|first=Danny|publisher=John Wiley & Sons Inc.|year=2011|isbn=9780470416839|location=|page=108}}</ref>\n\nThe centerpiece of the album was the 13-minute song cycle \"[[Ballet for a Girl in Buchannon]]\" written by trombone player [[James Pankow]], from which came the singles \"Make Me Smile\" and \"Color My World\". Guitarist [[Terry Kath]] also participated in an extended classically styled cycle of four pieces, three of which were co-written by arranger, composer, and pianist [[Peter Matz]].<ref name=\"Rhino CD booklet\">{{cite AV media notes|title=Chicago|year=2002|type=CD booklet|publisher=Rhino Entertainment Company|id=R2 76172|location=Burbank, California, USA|ref=}}</ref>{{rp|13}} Politically outspoken keyboardist [[Robert Lamm]] expresses his qualms in \"It Better End Soon\", another modular piece. Bassist [[Peter Cetera]] contributed his first song to Chicago with \"[[Where Do We Go from Here? (Chicago song)|Where Do We Go From Here?]]\".<ref name=classicrockrev />\n\n== Recording, production ==\nThe album was produced by [[James William Guercio]], who was Chicago's producer for its first eleven albums,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://chicagotheband.com/a-chicago-story/|title=A Chicago Story \u2013 Chicago|website=Chicagotheband.com|language=en-US|access-date=January 16, 2019}}</ref> and was recorded in less than a month, during August 1969.<ref name=\"classicrockrev\" />\n\nIn 1970, James Pankow said about the album, \" 'We . . . think it is better recorded and better played than the first. None of us feel, though, that we are really a recording group yet. We are all scared in the studio. We are really a live group.' \"<ref name=Rudis>{{Cite news|title=Chicago Is a Live Group|last=Rudis|first=Al|date=February 7, 1970|work=The Lincoln Journal Star|language=en-US|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27280217/lincoln_journal_star/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|access-date=January 16, 2019}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\n==Artwork, packaging==\nThe Chicago logo, which made its first appearance on the cover of this album, was designed by [[John Berg (art director)|John Berg]] and fashioned by Nick Fasciano,<ref name=\"Interview with John Berg at AIGA\">{{cite interview|first=John|last=Berg|interviewer=Paul Nini|publisher=American Institute of Graphic Arts|title=Across the Graphic Universe: an Interview with John Berg|url=http://www.aiga.org/across-the-graphic-universe-an-interview-with-john-berg/|date=October 30, 2007|accessdate=November 9, 2017}}</ref> who were both nominated for a [[Grammy Award for Best Recording Package|Grammy Award for Best Album Cover]] for their efforts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/john-berg|title=Grammy Awards: Artist: John Berg|website=Recording Academy Grammy Awards|language=en|access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/nick-fasciano|title=Grammy Awards: Artist: Nick Fasciano|website=Recording Academy Grammy Awards|language=en|access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> John Berg said the [[Coca-Cola]] logo was the inspiration for the Chicago logo.<ref name=\"Interview with John Berg at AIGA\"/> The cover art work is part of the permanent collection of the [[Museum of Modern Art]] in [[New York City]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moma.org/collection/works/189432|title=John Berg, Nick Fasciano. Cover for Chicago's second self-titled album|website=The Museum of Modern Art|language=en|access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> The band's official web site labels the cover design, \"silver bar.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagotheband.com/albums/chicago2.html|title=Albums: Chicago |website=Chicago - The Band|publisher=Chicago Touring|access-date=November 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe double-LP album's inner cover includes the playlist, the entire lyrics to \"It Better End Soon\", a \"Producer's Note\" stating, \"This endeavor should be experienced sequentially\", and a declaration written by Robert Lamm,<ref name=Ruhlmannp4>{{cite album-notes |title= Chicago Group Portrait (Box Set)|year= 1991|url= http://aln3.albumlinernotes.com/Chicago_Box_Set_-_Page_4.html|page=4|access-date= November 12, 2017|first= William James|last= Ruhlmann|format= CD booklet archived online|publisher= Columbia Records|location= New York City, NY}}</ref> \"With this album, we dedicate ourselves, our futures and our energies to the people of the revolution. And the revolution in all of its forms.\"<ref name= \"Chicago album\">{{Cite AV media notes |title=Chicago (album)|last=Chicago|year=1970 |type=Vinyl LP cover liner notes |publisher=Columbia |id=KGP 24  CS 9962  XSM 151734 |location=U.S.A. |ref=}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\nContemporary reviews for the album were mixed. In his review for the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times|Chicago Sun Times]]'', writer Al Rudis says Chicago's second album \"confirms\" that \"Chicago is one of the most exciting, most original, and most accomplished jazz-rock groups in existence.\"<ref name=Rudis/> whereas in a review for ''[[The Village Voice]]'', [[Robert Christgau]] gave ''Chicago'' a \"D+\" and called it \"sterile and stupid\", writing that if \"[[Duke Ellington]] never got away with an extended work for horns and meaningfulness [what] makes James William Guercio and the self-designated revolutionaries who are his cohorts think they can?\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|date=April 23, 1970|url=https://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/cg/cg9.php|title=Consumer Guide (9)|newspaper=[[The Village Voice]]|accessdate=November 7, 2017}}</ref> \n\nThere have been positive retrospective reviews. Lindsay Planer from [[AllMusic]] gave the album four-and-a-half out of five stars and said its songs \"underscore the solid foundation of complex jazz changes with heavy electric rock & roll that the band so brazenly forged on the first set\".<ref>{{AllMusic|class=album|id=r3844|label=Chicago|accessdate={{date|2017-02-17|mdy}}}}</ref> Jim Beviglia, writing for ''[[American Songwriter]],'' said, \"50 years after its release, ''Chicago II'' still stands as the one of the band\u2019s signature achievements. ...Listening to ''Chicago II'' now, it is remarkable just how smoothly the various pieces blend together.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://americansongwriter.com/chicago-ii-50th-anniversary-robert-lamm/jim-beviglia/|title=Robert Lamm Looks Back On The 50th Anniversary Of 'Chicago II'|last=Beviglia|first=Jim|date=February 25, 2020|website=American Songwriter|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=February 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n|+Grammy Awards\n! Year\n! Category\n! Work\n! Result\n! class=\"unsortable\" | {{Abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 1971\n| [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year#Recipients|Album of the Year]]\n| ''Chicago''\n| {{nom}}\n|align=\"center\"|<ref name=\"grammy\">{{cite web|title=Grammy Award Nominees and Winners \u2013 1971|url=http://www.awardsandshows.com/features/grammy-awards-1971-220.html|publisher=awardsandshows.com}}</ref> \n|-\n| [[Grammy Award for Best Pop Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocals#Recipients|Contemporary Vocal Group]]\n| ''Chicago''\n| {{nom}}\n|<ref name=\"grammy\" />\n|-\n| [[Grammy Award for Best Recording Package|Best Album Cover]]\n| ''Chicago'' (John Berg & Nick Fasciano)\n| {{nom}}\n|<ref name=\"grammy\" />\n|-\n|}\n\n'''Other honors'''\n<br />\n*1970: ''Chicago'', Best Album of 1970, ''[[Cashbox (magazine)|Cash Box]]''<ref>{{cite magazine |date=December 26, 1970 |title=Best Albums of 1970 |volume=XXXII|number=27|url=https://archive.org/details/cashbox32unse_19/page/47 |magazine=Cash Box |location=USA |publisher= |page=46|access-date=May 10, 2019|via=Internet Archive }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Chicago Coming to Hampton |date=May 29, 1973 |work=Daily Press |location=Newport News\u2013Hampton, Virginia, USA |page=10 |language=en-US |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/31444269/daily_press/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|access-date=May 10, 2019}}{{free access}}</ref>\n*1971: ''Chicago'', Best Small-Combo LP, ''[[Playboy]]'' Jazz & Pop Poll<ref name= \"Bondi 1971\" >{{Cite magazine |date=February 1971 |title=Jazz & Pop '71 |magazine=Playboy |publisher=HMH Publishing Co., Inc. }} available at, [http://bondiviewertest.azurewebsites.net/DataView/Article/PB?issueKey=19710201&articleKey=19710201093 Bondi Data Viewer] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171021220551/http://bondiviewertest.azurewebsites.net/DataView/Article/PB?issueKey=19710201&articleKey=19710201093 |date=October 21, 2017 |access-date=October 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| all_writing = \n| headline        = Side One\n| extra_column    = Vocals\n| title1          = Movin' In\n| length1         = 4:06\n| writer1         = [[James Pankow]]\n| extra1          = [[Terry Kath]]\n| title2          = The Road\n| length2         = 3:10\n| writer2         = [[Terry Kath]]\n| extra2          = [[Peter Cetera]]\n| title3          = Poem for the People\n| length3         = 4:25\n| writer3         = [[Robert Lamm]]\n| extra3          = Lamm/Cetera\n| title4          = In the Country\n| length4         = 6:34\n| writer4         = Kath\n| extra4          = Kath/Cetera\n| title5 = \n| length5 = \n| title6 = \n| length6 = \n| title7 = \n| length7 = \n| title8 = \n| length8 = \n| title9 = \n| length9 = \n| title10 = \n| length10 = \n| title11 = \n| length11 = \n| title12 = \n| length12 = \n| title13 = \n| length13 = \n| title14 = \n| length14 = \n| title15 = \n| length15 = \n| title16 = \n| length16 = \n| title17 = \n| length17 = \n| title18 = \n| length18 = \n| title19 = \n| length19 = \n| title20 = \n| length20 = \n| total_length = \n}}\n\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column    = Vocals\n| headline        = Side Two\n| title5          = Wake Up Sunshine\n| writer5         = Lamm\n| extra5          = Lamm/Cetera\n| length5         = 2:29\n| title6          = [[Ballet for a Girl in Buchannon]]\"\n# \"[[Make Me Smile]]\" (3:32)\n# \"So Much to Say, So Much to Give\" (1:04)\n# \"Anxiety's Moment\" (1:00)\n# \"West Virginia Fantasies\" (1:34)\n# \"[[Colour My World (Chicago song)|Colour My World]]\" (2:58)\n# \"To Be Free\" (1:21)\n# \"Now More Than Ever\" (1:27)<ref>individual times for Ballet taken from original LP KGP 24 CS 9962 XSM 151735</ref>\n| writer6         = Pankow\n| extra6          = <br />Kath<br />Lamm<br />[[Instrumental]]<br />Instrumental<br />Kath<br />Instrumental<br />Kath\n| length6         = 12:55\n}}\n\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column    = Vocals\n| headline        = Side Three\n| title7          = Fancy Colours\n| writer7         = Lamm\n| extra7          = Cetera\n| length7         = 5:10\n| title8          = [[25 or 6 to 4]]\n| writer8         = Lamm\n| extra8          = Cetera\n| length8         = 4:50\n| title9          = Memories of Love\"\n# \"Prelude\" (1:18)\n# \"A.M. Mourning\" (2:05)\n# \"P.M. Mourning\" (1:59)\n# \"Memories of Love (4:01)<ref>individual times for Memories of Love taken from original LP KGP 24 CS 9977 XSM 151852</ref>\n| writer9         = <br>Kath/[[Peter Matz]]<ref name=\"Rhino CD booklet\"/>{{rp|13}}<br>Kath/Matz<ref name=\"Rhino CD booklet\"/>{{rp|13}}<br>Kath/Matz<ref name=\"Rhino CD booklet\"/>{{rp|13}}<br>Kath\n| extra9          = <br />Instrumental<br />Instrumental<br />Instrumental<br />Kath\n| length9         = 9:12\n}}\n\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column    = Vocals\n| headline        = Side Four\n| title10         = It Better End Soon\"\n# \"1st Movement\" (2:30)\n# \"2nd Movement\" (3:47)\n# \"3rd Movement\" (3:19)\n# \"4th Movement\" (1:15)<ref>individual times for It Better End Soon taken from original LP KGP 24 CS 9977 XSM 151853</ref>\n| writer10        = <br>Lamm<br>Lamm/[[Walter Parazaider]]<br>Lamm/Kath<br>Lamm\n| extra10         = <br />Kath<br />Instrumental<br />Kath<br />Kath\n| length10        = 10:24\n\n| title11         = [[Where Do We Go from Here? (Chicago song)|Where Do We Go from Here?]]\n| writer11        = Cetera\n| extra11         = Cetera\n| length11        = 2:53\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\n===Chicago===\n*[[Peter Cetera]] \u2013 bass, vocals\n*[[Terry Kath]] \u2013 guitar, vocals\n*[[Robert Lamm]] \u2013 keyboards, vocals\n*[[Lee Loughnane]] \u2013 trumpet, vocals\n*[[James Pankow]] \u2013 trombone\n*[[Walter Parazaider]] \u2013 saxophone, flute, clarinet, vocals\n*[[Danny Seraphine]] \u2013 drums\n\n===Production===\n*[[James William Guercio]] \u2013 producer\n*Peter Matz \u2013 orchestration on \"Prelude\"\n*Donald Puluse \u2013 engineer\n*Brian Ross-Myring \u2013 engineer\n*Chris Hinshaw \u2013 engineer\n*Nick Fasciano \u2013 cover art\n*[[John Berg (art director)|John Berg]] \u2013 cover design\n*[[Herb Greene]] \u2013 photography and poster photos\n\n'''2002 reissue'''\n* Paul Klingberg \u2013 remixing\n*John Kellogg \u2013 remix producer\n*Joe Gastwirt \u2013 remastering\n*David Wild \u2013 liner notes\n\n==Charts==\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"2\" cellpadding=\"2\"\n!align=\"left\"|Year\n!align=\"left\"|Chart\n!align=\"left\"|Position\n!align=\"center\"|Ref\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|1970\n|align=\"left\"|''[[Billboard 200|Billboard]]'' [[Billboard 200|Pop Albums]]\n|align=\"left\"|4\n|<ref name=\"Billboard 200\"/>\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|1970\n|align=\"left\"|UK album chart\n|align=\"left\"|6\n|<ref name=\"UK album chart\"/>\n|-\n|}\n\n===Singles===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"2\" cellpadding=\"2\"\n!align=\"left\"|Year\n!align=\"left\"|Single\n!align=\"left\"|Chart\n!align=\"left\"|Position\n!align=\"center\"|Ref\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|1970\n|align=\"left\"|\"25 or 6 to 4\"\n|align=\"left\"|''[[Billboard Hot 100|Billboard]]'' [[Billboard Hot 100|Pop Singles]]\n|align=\"left\"|4\n|<ref name=\"Chicago Hot 100\"/>\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|1970\n|align=\"left\"|\"Make Me Smile\"\n|align=\"left\"|''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' Pop Singles\n|align=\"left\"|9\n|<ref name=\"Chicago Hot 100\"/>\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|1971\n|align=\"left\"|\"Colour My World\"\n|align=\"left\"|''Billboard'' Pop Singles\n|align=\"left\"|7\n|<ref name=\"Chicago Hot 100\"/>\n|-\n|}\n\n==Certifications==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"2\" cellpadding=\"2\"\n!align=\"left\"|Organization\n!align=\"left\"|Level\n!align=\"left\"|Date\n!align=\"center\"|Ref\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|RIAA \u2013 USA\n|align=\"left\"|Gold\n|align=\"left\"|April 13, 1970\n|<ref name=\"RIAA Chicago II\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?tab_active=default-award&ar=Chicago&ti=Chicago+II&lab=&genre=&format=&date_option=release&from=&to=&award=&type=&category=&adv=SEARCH#search_section|title=Gold & Platinum - RIAA: Chicago: Chicago II|work=RIAA|access-date=November 9, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref>\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|RIAA \u2013 USA\n|align=\"left\"|Platinum\n|align=\"left\"|August 9, 1991\n|<ref name=\"RIAA Chicago II\"/>\n|-\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=Note|refs=}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Chicagoband}}\n\n[[Category:Chicago (band) albums]]\n[[Category:1970 albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by James William Guercio]]\n[[Category:Columbia Records albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Chicago\n| type       = Studio album\n| artist     = [[Chicago (band)|Chicago]]\n| cover      = ChicagoAlbum.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = January 26, 1970<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.columbiarecords.com/timeline/#!date=1915-06-05_18:57:53!|website=360 Sound: The Columbia Records Story|title=125 Years of Columbia Records|publisher=Sony Music Entertainment|access-date=November 14, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171114143057/http://www.columbiarecords.com/timeline/#!date=1915-06-05_18:57:53!|archive-date=November 14, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| recorded   = August 1969\n| venue      =\n| studio     = [[CBS 30th Street Studio|Columbia Recording Studios]], [[New York City|New York]] and [[CBS Columbia Square|Columbia Studios]], [[Hollywood]]\n| genre      = [[Jazz fusion]], [[progressive rock]]\n| length     = 67:21\n| label      = [[Columbia Records|Columbia]]\n| producer   = [[James William Guercio]]\n| prev_title = [[Chicago Transit Authority (album)|Chicago Transit Authority]]\n| prev_year  = 1969\n| next_title = [[Chicago III]]\n| next_year  = 1971\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Chicago\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Make Me Smile]]/[[Colour My World (Chicago song)|Colour My World]]\n | single1date = March 1970\n | single2     = [[25 or 6 to 4]]\n | single2date = June 1970\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Chicago''''' is the second studio album by [[Chicago]]-based American [[rock and roll|rock]] band [[Chicago (band)|Chicago]].  Like their debut album, ''[[Chicago Transit Authority (album)|Chicago Transit Authority]]'', this was a double album.  It was their first album under the name Chicago (the band's prior name, Chicago Transit Authority, was changed due to a threatened lawsuit from the [[Chicago Transit Authority]]) and the first to use the now ubiquitous [[cursive writing|cursive]] Chicago logo on the cover. Released in January 1970 on [[Columbia Records]], ''Chicago'' was commercially successful. It was certified gold by the [[Recording Industry Association of America certification|Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA) in April of the same year of its release, and certified platinum in 1991. It reached No. 4 on the album charts in the United States and No. 6 on the album charts in the [[United Kingdom|UK]], and produced three top ten singles on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. The album received three [[Grammy Award]] nominations - for [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]], [[Grammy Award for Best Pop Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocals|Contemporary Vocal Group]], and [[Grammy Award for Best Recording Package|Best Album Cover]]. It was voted best album of 1970 by readers of ''[[Cashbox (magazine)|Cash Box]]'' magazine, and the 1971 best small-combo [[LP record|LP]] by readers of ''[[Playboy]]'' magazine.\n\n==History==\nThe album was released in 1970 after the band had shortened its name from \"The Chicago Transit Authority\" following the release of their self-titled [[Chicago Transit Authority (album)|debut album]] the previous year, in order to avoid legal action being threatened by the [[Chicago Transit Authority|actual mass-transit company]]. The official title of the album is ''Chicago'', although it came to be known as '''''Chicago II''''', keeping it in line with the succession of Roman numeral-titled albums that officially began with ''[[Chicago III]]'' in 1971.\n\n''Chicago Transit Authority'' was a success, yet ''Chicago'' is considered by many to be the group's breakthrough album, yielding three singles that made it into the top ten of the Billboard Hot 100, including \"[[Make Me Smile]]\" (number 9), \"[[Colour My World (Chicago song)|Colour My World]]\" (number 7), and \"[[25 or 6 to 4]]\" (number 4).<ref name=\"Chicago Hot 100\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/music/chicago/chart-history/hot-100|title=Chicago Chart History: Hot 100|work=Billboard|access-date=November 8, 2017}}</ref> \n\n''Chicago'' was released in January 1970 on Columbia Records and was an instant hit, reaching number 4 on the Billboard 200 in the United States<ref name=\"Billboard 200\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/music/chicago/chart-history/billboard-200|title=Chicago Chart History: Billboard 200|work=Billboard|access-date=November 8, 2017}}</ref> and number 6 in the UK.<ref name=\"UK album chart\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/search/albums/chicago/|title=Chicago {{!}} full Official Chart History {{!}} Official Charts Company|access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> Columbia Records was very active in promoting its quadraphonic four-channel surround-sound format in the mid-1970s, and nine of Chicago's first ten albums were made available in quad.  The quad mix features elements not heard in the standard stereo mix, including additional guitar work from Kath in \"25 Or 6 To 4\" and a different vocal take from Lamm in \"Wake Up Sunshine,\" which reveals a different lyric in the song's last line.\n\nIn 2002, ''Chicago'' was remastered and reissued on one CD by Rhino Records with the single versions of \"Make Me Smile\" and \"25 or 6 to 4\" as bonus tracks. Rhino released a DVD-Audio version of the album in 2003, featuring both Advanced Resolution Stereo and 5.1 surround sound mixes. In 2016, British producer and musician [[Steven Wilson]] remixed Chicago from the original multitrack tapes. This version was released on January 27, 2017 by Rhino Records.<ref>{{AllMusic |class=album/release|id=mr0004652426|tab= |label=Chicago II Steven Wilson Remix|last= |first= |accessdate={{date|2017-02-17|mdy}}}}</ref> A vinyl edition of the remix cut by Kevin Gray was released on August 11, 2017. [[Robert Lamm]] stated in an interview that the album has been nominated for the Grammy Hall of Fame more than once.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sunherald.com/news/local/news-columns-blogs/by-the-way/article181885271.html|title=Chicago\u2019s Robert Lamm on revisiting \u2018Chicago II\u2019 and the band\u2019s long and winding road|last=Clark|first=Jeff|date=October 31, 2017|work=Sun Herald|access-date=May 16, 2018|location=Gulfport, Mississippi, USA|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Musical style, writing, composition==\nIn a 2015 article, ''Classic Rock Review'' says the album saw Chicago's, \"full immersion into mainstream success while still building on their fusion of rock, funk and jazz.\"<ref name=classicrockrev>{{Cite web|url=http://www.classicrockreview.com/tag/midwest-artists/page/2/|title=Chicago II|date=July 3, 2015|website=Classic Rock Review|language=en-US|access-date=January 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn Danny Seraphine's book ''Street Player'', he describes it this way: \"In between the dates of our touring schedule, we somehow found the opportunity to jump into CBS Studios in Los Angeles and record a second album in August 1969. Whereas the first record was a compilation of raw energy, we took a more controlled approach to our new effort.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=\"Street Player: My Chicago Story|last=Seraphine|first=Danny|publisher=John Wiley & Sons Inc.|year=2011|isbn=9780470416839|location=|page=108}}</ref>\n\nThe centerpiece of the album was the 13-minute song cycle \"[[Ballet for a Girl in Buchannon]]\" written by trombone player [[James Pankow]], from which came the singles \"Make Me Smile\" and \"Color My World\". Guitarist [[Terry Kath]] also participated in an extended classically styled cycle of four pieces, three of which were co-written by arranger, composer, and pianist [[Peter Matz]].<ref name=\"Rhino CD booklet\">{{cite AV media notes|title=Chicago|year=2002|type=CD booklet|publisher=Rhino Entertainment Company|id=R2 76172|location=Burbank, California, USA|ref=}}</ref>{{rp|13}} Politically outspoken keyboardist [[Robert Lamm]] expresses his qualms in \"It Better End Soon\", another modular piece. Bassist [[Peter Cetera]] contributed his first song to Chicago with \"[[Where Do We Go from Here? (Chicago song)|Where Do We Go From Here?]]\".<ref name=classicrockrev />\n\n== Recording, production ==\nThe album was produced by [[James William Guercio]], who was Chicago's producer for its first eleven albums,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://chicagotheband.com/a-chicago-story/|title=A Chicago Story \u2013 Chicago|website=Chicagotheband.com|language=en-US|access-date=January 16, 2019}}</ref> and was recorded in less than a month, during August 1969.<ref name=\"classicrockrev\" />\n\nIn 1970, James Pankow said about the album, \" 'We . . . think it is better recorded and better played than the first. None of us feel, though, that we are really a recording group yet. We are all scared in the studio. We are really a live group.' \"<ref name=Rudis>{{Cite news|title=Chicago Is a Live Group|last=Rudis|first=Al|date=February 7, 1970|work=The Lincoln Journal Star|language=en-US|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27280217/lincoln_journal_star/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|access-date=January 16, 2019}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\n==Artwork, packaging==\nThe Chicago logo, which made its first appearance on the cover of this album, was designed by [[John Berg (art director)|John Berg]] and fashioned by Nick Fasciano,<ref name=\"Interview with John Berg at AIGA\">{{cite interview|first=John|last=Berg|interviewer=Paul Nini|publisher=American Institute of Graphic Arts|title=Across the Graphic Universe: an Interview with John Berg|url=http://www.aiga.org/across-the-graphic-universe-an-interview-with-john-berg/|date=October 30, 2007|accessdate=November 9, 2017}}</ref> who were both nominated for a [[Grammy Award for Best Recording Package|Grammy Award for Best Album Cover]] for their efforts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/john-berg|title=Grammy Awards: Artist: John Berg|website=Recording Academy Grammy Awards|language=en|access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/nick-fasciano|title=Grammy Awards: Artist: Nick Fasciano|website=Recording Academy Grammy Awards|language=en|access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> John Berg said the [[Coca-Cola]] logo was the inspiration for the Chicago logo.<ref name=\"Interview with John Berg at AIGA\"/> The cover art work is part of the permanent collection of the [[Museum of Modern Art]] in [[New York City]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moma.org/collection/works/189432|title=John Berg, Nick Fasciano. Cover for Chicago's second self-titled album|website=The Museum of Modern Art|language=en|access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> The band's official web site labels the cover design, \"silver bar.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagotheband.com/albums/chicago2.html|title=Albums: Chicago |website=Chicago - The Band|publisher=Chicago Touring|access-date=November 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe double-LP album's inner cover includes the playlist, the entire lyrics to \"It Better End Soon\", a \"Producer's Note\" stating, \"This endeavor should be experienced sequentially\", and a declaration written by Robert Lamm,<ref name=Ruhlmannp4>{{cite album-notes |title= Chicago Group Portrait (Box Set)|year= 1991|url= http://aln3.albumlinernotes.com/Chicago_Box_Set_-_Page_4.html|page=4|access-date= November 12, 2017|first= William James|last= Ruhlmann|format= CD booklet archived online|publisher= Columbia Records|location= New York City, NY}}</ref> \"With this album, we dedicate ourselves, our futures and our energies to the people of the revolution. And the revolution in all of its forms.\"<ref name= \"Chicago album\">{{Cite AV media notes |title=Chicago (album)|last=Chicago|year=1970 |type=Vinyl LP cover liner notes |publisher=Columbia |id=KGP 24  CS 9962  XSM 151734 |location=U.S.A. |ref=}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\nContemporary reviews for the album were mixed. In his review for the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times|Chicago Sun Times]]'', writer Al Rudis says Chicago's second album \"confirms\" that \"Chicago is one of the most exciting, most original, and most accomplished jazz-rock groups in existence.\"<ref name=Rudis/> whereas in a review for ''[[The Village Voice]]'', [[Robert Christgau]] gave ''Chicago'' a \"D+\" and called it \"sterile and stupid\", writing that if \"[[Duke Ellington]] never got away with an extended work for horns and meaningfulness [what] makes James William Guercio and the self-designated revolutionaries who are his cohorts think they can?\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|date=April 23, 1970|url=https://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/cg/cg9.php|title=Consumer Guide (9)|newspaper=[[The Village Voice]]|accessdate=November 7, 2017}}</ref> \n\nThere have been positive retrospective reviews. Lindsay Planer from [[AllMusic]] gave the album four-and-a-half out of five stars and said its songs \"underscore the solid foundation of complex jazz changes with heavy electric rock & roll that the band so brazenly forged on the first set\".<ref>{{AllMusic|class=album|id=r3844|label=Chicago|accessdate={{date|2017-02-17|mdy}}}}</ref> Jim Beviglia, writing for ''[[American Songwriter]],'' said, \"50 years after its release, ''Chicago II'' still stands as the one of the band\u2019s signature achievements. ...Listening to ''Chicago II'' now, it is remarkable just how smoothly the various pieces blend together.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://americansongwriter.com/chicago-ii-50th-anniversary-robert-lamm/jim-beviglia/|title=Robert Lamm Looks Back On The 50th Anniversary Of 'Chicago II'|last=Beviglia|first=Jim|date=February 25, 2020|website=American Songwriter|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=February 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n|+Grammy Awards\n! Year\n! Category\n! Work\n! Result\n! class=\"unsortable\" | {{Abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 1971\n| [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year#Recipients|Album of the Year]]\n| ''Chicago''\n| {{nom}}\n|align=\"center\"|<ref name=\"grammy\">{{cite web|title=Grammy Award Nominees and Winners \u2013 1971|url=http://www.awardsandshows.com/features/grammy-awards-1971-220.html|publisher=awardsandshows.com}}</ref> \n|-\n| [[Grammy Award for Best Pop Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocals#Recipients|Contemporary Vocal Group]]\n| ''Chicago''\n| {{nom}}\n|<ref name=\"grammy\" />\n|-\n| [[Grammy Award for Best Recording Package|Best Album Cover]]\n| ''Chicago'' (John Berg & Nick Fasciano)\n| {{nom}}\n|<ref name=\"grammy\" />\n|-\n|}\n\n'''Other honors'''\n<br />\n*1970: ''Chicago'', Best Album of 1970, ''[[Cashbox (magazine)|Cash Box]]''<ref>{{cite magazine |date=December 26, 1970 |title=Best Albums of 1970 |volume=XXXII|number=27|url=https://archive.org/details/cashbox32unse_19/page/47 |magazine=Cash Box |location=USA |publisher= |page=46|access-date=May 10, 2019|via=Internet Archive }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Chicago Coming to Hampton |date=May 29, 1973 |work=Daily Press |location=Newport News\u2013Hampton, Virginia, USA |page=10 |language=en-US |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/31444269/daily_press/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|access-date=May 10, 2019}}{{free access}}</ref>\n*1971: ''Chicago'', Best Small-Combo LP, ''[[Playboy]]'' Jazz & Pop Poll<ref name= \"Bondi 1971\" >{{Cite magazine |date=February 1971 |title=Jazz & Pop '71 |magazine=Playboy |publisher=HMH Publishing Co., Inc. }} available at, [http://bondiviewertest.azurewebsites.net/DataView/Article/PB?issueKey=19710201&articleKey=19710201093 Bondi Data Viewer] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171021220551/http://bondiviewertest.azurewebsites.net/DataView/Article/PB?issueKey=19710201&articleKey=19710201093 |date=October 21, 2017 |access-date=October 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| all_writing = \n| headline        = Side One\n| extra_column    = Vocals\n| title1          = Movin' In\n| length1         = 4:06\n| writer1         = [[James Pankow]]\n| extra1          = [[Terry Kath]]\n| title2          = The Road\n| length2         = 3:10\n| writer2         = [[Terry Kath]]\n| extra2          = [[Peter Cetera]]\n| title3          = Poem for the People\n| length3         = 4:25\n| writer3         = [[Robert Lamm]]\n| extra3          = Lamm/Cetera\n| title4          = In the Country\n| length4         = 6:34\n| writer4         = Kath\n| extra4          = Kath/Cetera\n| title5 = \n| length5 = \n| title6 = \n| length6 = \n| title7 = \n| length7 = \n| title8 = \n| length8 = \n| title9 = \n| length9 = \n| title10 = \n| length10 = \n| title11 = \n| length11 = \n| title12 = \n| length12 = \n| title13 = \n| length13 = \n| title14 = \n| length14 = \n| title15 = \n| length15 = \n| title16 = \n| length16 = \n| title17 = \n| length17 = \n| title18 = \n| length18 = \n| title19 = \n| length19 = \n| title20 = \n| length20 = \n| total_length = \n}}\n\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column    = Vocals\n| headline        = Side Two\n| title5          = Wake Up Sunshine\n| writer5         = Lamm\n| extra5          = Lamm/Cetera\n| length5         = 2:29\n| title6          = [[Ballet for a Girl in Buchannon]]\"\n# \"[[Make Me Smile]]\" (3:32)\n# \"So Much to Say, So Much to Give\" (1:04)\n# \"Anxiety's Moment\" (1:00)\n# \"West Virginia Fantasies\" (1:34)\n# \"[[Colour My World (Chicago song)|Colour My World]]\" (2:58)\n# \"To Be Free\" (1:21)\n# \"Now More Than Ever\" (1:27)<ref>individual times for Ballet taken from original LP KGP 24 CS 9962 XSM 151735</ref>\n| writer6         = Pankow\n| extra6          = <br />Kath<br />Lamm<br />[[Instrumental]]<br />Instrumental<br />Kath<br />Instrumental<br />Kath\n| length6         = 12:55\n}}\n\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column    = Vocals\n| headli